{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Jes\u00fas Perera", "text_new": "{{Spanish name 2|Perera|L\u00f3pez}} \n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jes\u00fas Perera\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Jes\u00fas Perera L\u00f3pez \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1980|4|12|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Olivenza]], Spain\n| height = {{Height|m=1.76|precision=0}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[CD Badajoz|Badajoz]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20132001 \n| years2 = 2001\u20132003 \n| years3 = 2003\u20132005 \n| years4 = 2005\u20132008 \n| years5 = 2008\u20132010 \n| years6 = 2009\u20132010 \n| years7 = 2010\u20132011\n| years8 = 2011\u20132012\n| years9 = 2013\u20132014\n| years10 = 2014\u20132016\n| clubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] \n| clubs2 = [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9|Albacete]] \n| clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] \n| clubs4 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] \n| clubs5 = [[Rayo Vallecano]] \n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Elche CF|Elche]] (loan) \n| clubs7 = [[Elche CF|Elche]]\n| clubs8 = [[CD Atl\u00e9tico Baleares|Atl\u00e9tico Baleares]]\n| clubs9 = [[Gimn\u00e0stic de Tarragona|Gimn\u00e0stic]]\n| clubs10 = [[M\u00e9rida AD|M\u00e9rida]]\n| caps1 = 77  \n| caps2 = 73  \n| caps3 = 32  \n| caps4 = 81  \n| caps5 = 15  \n| caps6 = 19  \n| caps7 = 23\n| caps8 = 50\n| caps9 = 47\n| caps10 = 41\n| totalcaps = 458       \n| goals1 = 22  \n| goals2 = 29  \n| goals3 = 7  \n| goals4 = 26  \n| goals5 = 3  \n| goals6 = 5  \n| goals7 = 2\n| goals8 = 28\n| goals9 = 11\n| goals10 = 24\n| totalgoals = 157\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Jes\u00fas Perera L\u00f3pez''' (born 12 April 1980) is a Spanish former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nHe played 186 [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] games over eight seasons, scoring a combined 60 goals for [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]], [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9|Albacete]], [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]], [[Rayo Vallecano]] and [[Elche CF|Elche]]. He added in 66 matches and 12 goals in [[La Liga]], in an 18-year professional career.\n\n==Club career==\nPerera was born in [[Olivenza]], [[Province of Badajoz]]. A prolific scorer in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]], notably scoring 22 league goals for [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9]] in the [[2002\u201303 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2002\u201303 season]],<ref name=PICHICHI>[http://archivo.marca.com/futbol/pichichi02_03_segunda.html Jes\u00fas Perera, Pichichi 2003 en Segunda (Jes\u00fas Perera, 2003 ''Pichichi'' in ''Segunda'')]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 29 June 2003 (in Spanish)</ref> he struggled to maintain the same rate in the top flight in his four [[La Liga]] campaigns (two with both [[RCD Mallorca]] and [[RC Celta de Vigo]]).<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=321695.html Celta seal double deal]; UEFA, 1 August 2005</ref> His best input came in [[2003\u201304 La Liga|2003\u201304]], as he netted six times for the [[Balearic Islands]] club.\n\nIn the [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2007\u201308 season]], Perera scored 15 league goals for a [[Galicia (Spain)|Galician]] squad that failed to return to the top level \u2013 he would immediately change teams again, joining [[Rayo Vallecano]].<ref>[http://www.futboldesegunda.com/perera-ya-entrena-con-el-rayo/ Perera ya entrena con el Rayo (Perera already training with Rayo)]; F\u00fatbol de Segunda, 27 August 2008 (in Spanish)</ref> Rarely used during [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the campaign]], he was loaned in July 2009 two another side in that tier, [[Elche CF]], in a [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|season]]-long move;<ref>[http://www.as.com/futbol/articulo/jesus-perera-llega-elche-cedido/20090724dasdasftb_33/Tes Jes\u00fas Perera llega al Elche cedido por el Rayo Vallecano (Jes\u00fas Perera arrives at Elche on loan from Rayo Vallecano)]; [[Diario AS]], 24 July 2009 (in Spanish)</ref> the deal was made permanent in August 2010.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2010/08/11/futbol/equipos/elche/1281528803.html Cambio de 'cromos' entre Elche y Rayo Vallecano (Change of 'cards' between Elche and Rayo Vallecano)]; Marca, 11 August 2010 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, Perera signed with [[CD Atl\u00e9tico Baleares]] of the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third level]].<ref>[http://mallorcaconfidencial.com/20110730_60867-el-baleares-ficha-a-jesus-perera.html El Baleares ficha a Jes\u00fas Perera (Baleares signs Jes\u00fas Perera)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716020221/http://mallorcaconfidencial.com/20110730_60867-el-baleares-ficha-a-jesus-perera.html|date=16 July 2012}}; Mallorca Confidencial, 30 July 2011 (in Spanish)</ref> In [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his first and only full season]] he netted 23 goals in only 32 matches, but his team failed to promote eventually.\n\nIn January 2013, Perera joined another club in division three, [[Gimn\u00e0stic de Tarragona]].<ref>[http://www.gimnasticdetarragona.com/cat2/act-noticia.php?id=5115 Jes\u00fas Perera ja vesteix de grana (Jes\u00fas Perera already wears ''grana'')]; Gimn\u00e0stic Tarragona, 2 January 2013 (in Catalan)</ref> After one-and-a-half seasons with the [[Catalonia|Catalans]], he left after the expiry of his contract.<ref>[http://www.gimnasticdetarragona.com/cat2/act-noticia.php?id=6021 Jes\u00fas Perera finalitza el seu contracte amb el N\u00e0stic (Jes\u00fas Perera ends his contract with ''N\u00e0stic'')]; Gimn\u00e0stic Tarragona, 28 June 2014 (in Catalan)</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2014, Perera signed for [[M\u00e9rida AD]] in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|fourth tier]].<ref>[http://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/tercera-division/385182-fichaje-bomba-jesus-perera-es-nuevo-jugador-del-merida-ad.html Jes\u00fas Perera es nuevo jugador del M\u00e9rida AD (Jes\u00fas Perera is a new player of M\u00e9rida AD)]; [[Vavel]], 29 August 2014 (in Spanish)</ref> He was top scorer with 23 goals in [[2014\u201315 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|his first season]] as they won promotion, but retired at the age of 36 at the conclusion of [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the following campaign]], in which he was troubled by a knee injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2016/04/28/segunda-b/640050-jesus-perera-cuelga-las-botas.html|title=Jes\u00fas Perera cuelga las botas|trans-title=Jes\u00fas Perera hangs up boots|publisher=Vavel|language=es|date=28 April 2016|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Individual===\n*[[Pichichi Trophy]] ([[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]): [[2002\u201303 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2002\u201303]]<ref name=PICHICHI/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1253|Jes\u00fas Perera}}\n*{{Futbolme profile|18415|Jes\u00fas Perera}}\n*{{Soccerway|jesus-perera-lopez/58684|Jes\u00fas Perera}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perera, Jose Jesus}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Olivenza]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Extremaduran footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:Albacete Balompi\u00e9 players]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo players]]\n[[Category:Rayo Vallecano players]]\n[[Category:Elche CF players]]\n[[Category:CD Atl\u00e9tico Baleares footballers]]\n[[Category:Gimn\u00e0stic de Tarragona footballers]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9rida AD players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name 2|Perera|L\u00f3pez}} \n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jes\u00fas Perera\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Jes\u00fas Perera L\u00f3pez \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1980|4|12|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Olivenza]], Spain\n| height = {{Height|m=1.76|precision=0}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[CD Badajoz|Badajoz]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20132001 \n| years2 = 2001\u20132003 \n| years3 = 2003\u20132005 \n| years4 = 2005\u20132008 \n| years5 = 2008\u20132010 \n| years6 = 2009\u20132010 \n| years7 = 2010\u20132011\n| years8 = 2011\u20132012\n| years9 = 2013\u20132014\n| years10 = 2014\u20132016\n| clubs1 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] \n| clubs2 = [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9|Albacete]] \n| clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] \n| clubs4 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] \n| clubs5 = [[Rayo Vallecano]] \n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Elche CF|Elche]] (loan) \n| clubs7 = [[Elche CF|Elche]]\n| clubs8 = [[CD Atl\u00e9tico Baleares|Atl\u00e9tico Baleares]]\n| clubs9 = [[Gimn\u00e0stic de Tarragona|Gimn\u00e0stic]]\n| clubs10 = [[M\u00e9rida AD|M\u00e9rida]]\n| caps1 = 77  \n| caps2 = 73  \n| caps3 = 32  \n| caps4 = 81  \n| caps5 = 15  \n| caps6 = 19  \n| caps7 = 23\n| caps8 = 50\n| caps9 = 47\n| caps10 = 41\n| totalcaps = 458       \n| goals1 = 22  \n| goals2 = 29  \n| goals3 = 7  \n| goals4 = 26  \n| goals5 = 3  \n| goals6 = 5  \n| goals7 = 2\n| goals8 = 28\n| goals9 = 11\n| goals10 = 24\n| totalgoals = 157\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Jes\u00fas Perera L\u00f3pez''' (born 12 April 1980) is a Spanish former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nHe played 186 [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] games during eight seasons, scoring a combined 60 goals for [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]], [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9|Albacete]], [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]], [[Rayo Vallecano]] and [[Elche CF|Elche]]. He added in 66 matches and 12 goals in [[La Liga]], in an 18-year professional career.\n\n==Club career==\nPerera was born in [[Olivenza]], [[Province of Badajoz]]. A prolific scorer in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]], notably scoring 22 league goals for [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9]] in the [[2002\u201303 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2002\u201303 season]],<ref name=PICHICHI>[http://archivo.marca.com/futbol/pichichi02_03_segunda.html Jes\u00fas Perera, Pichichi 2003 en Segunda (Jes\u00fas Perera, 2003 ''Pichichi'' in ''Segunda'')]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 29 June 2003 (in Spanish)</ref> he struggled to maintain the same rate in the top flight in his four [[La Liga]] campaigns (two with both [[RCD Mallorca]] and [[RC Celta de Vigo]]).<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=321695.html Celta seal double deal]; UEFA, 1 August 2005</ref> His best input came in [[2003\u201304 La Liga|2003\u201304]], as he netted six times for the [[Balearic Islands]] club.\n\nIn the [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2007\u201308 season]], Perera scored 15 league goals for a [[Galicia (Spain)|Galician]] squad that failed to return to the top level \u2013 he would immediately change teams again, joining [[Rayo Vallecano]].<ref>[http://www.futboldesegunda.com/perera-ya-entrena-con-el-rayo/ Perera ya entrena con el Rayo (Perera already training with Rayo)]; F\u00fatbol de Segunda, 27 August 2008 (in Spanish)</ref> Rarely used during [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the campaign]], he was loaned in July 2009 two another side in that tier, [[Elche CF]], in a [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|season]]-long move;<ref>[http://www.as.com/futbol/articulo/jesus-perera-llega-elche-cedido/20090724dasdasftb_33/Tes Jes\u00fas Perera llega al Elche cedido por el Rayo Vallecano (Jes\u00fas Perera arrives at Elche on loan from Rayo Vallecano)]; [[Diario AS]], 24 July 2009 (in Spanish)</ref> the deal was made permanent in August 2010.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2010/08/11/futbol/equipos/elche/1281528803.html Cambio de 'cromos' entre Elche y Rayo Vallecano (Change of 'cards' between Elche and Rayo Vallecano)]; Marca, 11 August 2010 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, Perera signed with [[CD Atl\u00e9tico Baleares]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third level]].<ref>[http://mallorcaconfidencial.com/20110730_60867-el-baleares-ficha-a-jesus-perera.html El Baleares ficha a Jes\u00fas Perera (Baleares signs Jes\u00fas Perera)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716020221/http://mallorcaconfidencial.com/20110730_60867-el-baleares-ficha-a-jesus-perera.html|date=16 July 2012}}; Mallorca Confidencial, 30 July 2011 (in Spanish)</ref> In [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his first and only full season]] he netted 23 goals in only 32 matches, but his team failed to promote eventually.\n\nIn January 2013, Perera joined another club in division three, [[Gimn\u00e0stic de Tarragona]].<ref>[http://www.gimnasticdetarragona.com/cat2/act-noticia.php?id=5115 Jes\u00fas Perera ja vesteix de grana (Jes\u00fas Perera already wears ''grana'')]; Gimn\u00e0stic Tarragona, 2 January 2013 (in Catalan)</ref> After one-and-a-half seasons with the [[Catalonia|Catalans]], he left after the expiry of his contract.<ref>[http://www.gimnasticdetarragona.com/cat2/act-noticia.php?id=6021 Jes\u00fas Perera finalitza el seu contracte amb el N\u00e0stic (Jes\u00fas Perera ends his contract with ''N\u00e0stic'')]; Gimn\u00e0stic Tarragona, 28 June 2014 (in Catalan)</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2014, Perera signed for [[M\u00e9rida AD]] in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|fourth tier]].<ref>[http://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/tercera-division/385182-fichaje-bomba-jesus-perera-es-nuevo-jugador-del-merida-ad.html Jes\u00fas Perera es nuevo jugador del M\u00e9rida AD (Jes\u00fas Perera is a new player of M\u00e9rida AD)]; [[Vavel]], 29 August 2014 (in Spanish)</ref> He was top scorer with 23 goals in [[2014\u201315 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|his first season]] as they won promotion, but retired at the age of 36 at the conclusion of [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the following campaign]], in which he was troubled by a knee injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2016/04/28/segunda-b/640050-jesus-perera-cuelga-las-botas.html|title=Jes\u00fas Perera cuelga las botas|trans-title=Jes\u00fas Perera hangs up boots|publisher=Vavel|language=es|date=28 April 2016|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Individual===\n*[[Pichichi Trophy]] ([[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]): [[2002\u201303 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2002\u201303]]<ref name=PICHICHI/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1253|Jes\u00fas Perera}}\n*{{Futbolme profile|18415|Jes\u00fas Perera}}\n*{{Soccerway|jesus-perera-lopez/58684|Jes\u00fas Perera}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perera, Jose Jesus}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Olivenza]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Extremaduran footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:Albacete Balompi\u00e9 players]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo players]]\n[[Category:Rayo Vallecano players]]\n[[Category:Elche CF players]]\n[[Category:CD Atl\u00e9tico Baleares footballers]]\n[[Category:Gimn\u00e0stic de Tarragona footballers]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9rida AD players]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor tidyups overall, nothing hurt whatsoever.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Jes%C3%BAs_Perera"}
{"title_page": "Charles Curtis (botanist)", "text_new": "'''Charles Curtis''' (1853 \u2013 23 August 1928) was an English [[botanist]] who was sent by [[James Veitch & Sons]] to search for new plant species in [[Madagascar]], [[Borneo]], [[Sumatra]], [[Java]] and the [[Moluccas]], before settling in [[Penang]], where he became the first superintendent of the [[Penang Botanic Gardens]].\n\n==Early days==\nCurtis was born in [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]],<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>  the youngest of four brothers.<ref name = \"Orchids\">{{cite web| url= http://www.orchids.co.in/orchidologists/charles-curtis.shtm|title = Charles Curtis (1853\u20131928) |author= |publisher = www.orchids.co.in|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref> His paternal grandfather, a [[Normans|Norman]] by the name of Courtois, had settled at Barnstaple many years previously. Like his brothers, Curtis worked as a garden boy at the local Bale's Nursery.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> On completing his education, Curtis joined [[James Veitch & Sons]]' Royal Exotic Nursery at [[Chelsea, London]] in 1874, where he received his botanical training in the \"New Plant Department\".<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>\n\n==Plant hunting==\nIn 1878, [[Harry Veitch]] despatched him to [[Mauritius]] and [[Madagascar]], from where he sent seeds of ''[[Nepenthes madagascariensis]]'', a species of [[pitcher plant]],<ref name = \"HV85\">{{cite book | author=[[James Herbert Veitch]]| title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher=[[Caradoc Doy]] | year=2006|edition=reprint|page=85| isbn=0-9553515-0-2}}</ref> and various other tropical plants, including ''[[Angraecum sesquipedale]]''.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> Unfortunately, following \"treachery\" by one of the African helpers, who cut the rope which held the raft on which the plants were being floated downriver, the first consignment of plants collected was lost and, as a result, the collecting work had to be repeated.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\n[[Image:MN561 A New Pitcher Plant from the Limestone Mountains of Sarawak, Borneo.jpg|thumb|left|[[Marianne North]]'s painting of ''[[Nepenthes northiana]]'', showing a lower and an upper pitcher]]\nCurtis returned to England in 1879, but a year later was sent to the [[Dutch East Indies]], where he explored [[Borneo]], [[Sumatra]], [[Java]] and the [[Moluccas]]. Veitch instructed him to collect specimens of ''[[Nepenthes northiana]]'', which had been discovered by [[Marianne North]] in Borneo, although the precise locality where the plant grew was unknown.<ref name = \"HV85\"/> On the trip to Borneo, Curtis was accompanied by a young gardener, [[David Burke (botanist)|David Burke]],<ref name = \"HV85\"/> who later became a [[plant collector]] himself. The search for the elusive pitcher plant was unsuccessful, but the pair discovered many other species, including many interesting stove ([[Greenhouse|hot-house]]) plants, palms, and orchids. At the end of the trip, Curtis accompanied Burke to [[Singapore]], from where Burke returned to England with the collection of plants, including large consignments of the  [[slipper orchid]]s, ''[[Paphiopedilum stonei]]'' and ''[[Paphiopedilum lowii|P. lowii]]'',<ref name = \"HV86\"/> as well as many [[Vanda]]s, [[Rhododendron]]s, and the beautiful foliage plant for British hot-houses, ''[[Leea amabilis]]''.<ref name = \"HV86\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=86| isbn= }}</ref><ref name = \"HV271\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=271| isbn= }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Paphiopedilum superbiens Orchi 05.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Paphiopedilum superbiens]]'' ]]\nFrom Singapore, Curtis travelled to [[Pontianak, Indonesia|Pontianak]] in Dutch Borneo, with the special object of obtaining a consignment of ''[[Phalaenopsis violacea]]'', then known in England but still rare. He was successful in locating the plant, but again, owing to a mishap with the boat, a month's collections and all his clothes and instruments were lost, and he narrowly escaped with his life.<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n\nIn 1882, Curtis eventually located ''[[Nepenthes northiana]]'' in Borneo and sent seeds back to Chelsea, as well as ''[[Nepenthes stenophylla|N. stenophylla]]'' and seed from a plant that became known as ''[[Nepenthes maxima|N. curtisii]]'', although now known as ''[[Nepenthes maxima|N. maxima]]''. Curtis was not meticulous in recording where he located individual plants \u2013 although it was originally believed that he collected ''N. curtisii'' in Borneo, [[Charles Clarke (botanist)|Charles Clarke]] points out that he also visited [[Sulawesi]] on the same trip, and ''N. maxima'' is common there.<ref name=Clarke>Clarke, C.M. 1997. ''Nepenthes of Borneo''.  Natural History Publications (Borneo), Kota Kinabalu.</ref> He also sent back the orchid which was originally named ''[[Paphiopedilum curtisii]]'',<ref name = \"OSCOV\"/> although now known as a synonym for ''[[Paphiopedilum superbiens]]'';<ref name = \"Commons\"/> Curtis did not reveal where he found the plants, other than saying that this was in [[Sumatra]].<ref name = \"OSCOV\"/>\n\nAccording to the account in ''[[Hortus Veitchii]]'', Curtis had been commissioned to go in search of ''Nepenthes northiana'', and <blockquote>\"after long and unsuccessful effort, Curtis gave up hope, under the impression that Miss North had been wrongly informed, but fortunately before leaving the district it occurred to him to look over a steep escarpment in the hill-side, accomplished by lying prostrate on the ground, when to his great joy he discovered the long-looked-for plant some distance below. He succeeded in gathering ripe capsules, and lost no time in transmitting them to Chelsea, where the seed soon germinated\",<ref name = \"HV485\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=485| isbn= }}</ref></blockquote> and was introduced in the James Veitch & Sons catalogue in 1883.\n\nOther plants introduced to England by Curtis, include two species of [[Rhododendron subgenus Vireya|Vireya rhododendron]] \u2013  ''[[Rhododendron multicolor]]'' (with the red variety ''Curtisii'' named after him)<ref name = \"HV286\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=286| isbn= }}</ref> and ''[[Rhododendron teysmannii|R. teysmannii]]'' (now considered to be subspecies of ''[[Rhododendron javanicum|R. javanicum]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.vireya.net/history.htm|title = The History of Vireya Rhododendron Culture|author= Chris Callard|publisher = www.vireya.net|date=30 April 2008|accessdate=16 December 2008}}</ref> \u2013 before he terminated his engagement with Veitch early in 1884.<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n[[Image:Nepenthes maxima Sulawesi1.jpg|200px|right|thumb|''[[Nepenthes maxima]]'']]\nAmongst the many plant species named after Curtis in recognition of his services to botany and horticulture were the following:\n \n*''[[Acanthephippium curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV111\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=111| isbn= }}</ref> \n*''[[Cirrhopetalum curtisii]]''<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.yonggee.name/Notes/Cirr_curtisii.htm|title = Cirrhopetalum curtisii|author= Orchid Species Society|publisher =www.yonggee.name|date=June 2003|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n*''[[Gastrochilus curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n*''[[Luisia curtisii]]''<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.orchidfoto.com/thumbnails.php?album=182 |title = Luisia curtisii|author= National Parks, Singapore|publisher =www.orchidfoto.com|date= |accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n*''[[Medinilla curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV273\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=273| isbn= }}</ref> \n*''[[Nepenthes curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV86\"/> (subsequently synonymised with ''[[Nepenthes maxima]]'')\n*''[[Paphiopedilum curtisii]]''<ref name=\"OSCOV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscov.asn.au/articles2/paph3.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050508012449/http://www.oscov.asn.au/articles2/paph3.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 May 2005|title=The Lost Slippers|author=Alan Hope and Brian Milligan|publisher=Orchids Society Council of Victoria|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref><ref name = \"HV123\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=123| isbn= }}</ref> (subsequently synonymised with ''[[Paphiopedilum superbiens]]'')<ref name = \"Commons\">{{cite web| url= http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Paphiopedilum_superbiens|title = Paphiopedilum superbiens|author= |publisher =commons.wikimedia.org|date= |accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n*''[[Pentace curtisii]]''<ref>{{cite web| url= http://floraweb.nparks.gov.sg/search/viewDetail.action;jsessionid=1F8640C2515B9F16B08C5470E8E61742?pgId=1913590059831626&key=3| title= Pentace curtisii| author= National Parks, Singapore| publisher= www.nparks.gov.sg| date= | accessdate= 6 November 2008}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*''[[Rhododendron multicolor]]'' var. ''curtisii''<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n*''[[Shorea curtisii]]'' (dark red meranti)<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.nparks.gov.sg/cms/index.php?option=com_g2bridge&view=gallery&Itemid=94&g2_itemId=1924|title = Shorea curtisii|author= National Parks, Singapore|publisher =www.nparks.gov.sg|date= 14 May 2008|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe was also honoured by the genus ''Curtisina'',<ref name = \"Jones14\"/> but the only member of the genus, ''Curtisina penangensis'', was subsequently identified as a [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] synonym of ''[[Dacryodes longifolia]]''.<ref name = \"TKB\">{{cite web| url= https://doi.org/10.1663%2F0007-196X%282003%2954%5B266%3ANODVIA%5D2.0.CO%3B2|title = Notes on Dacryodes |author= Douglas C. Daly|publisher = SpringerLink|date= 12 February 2008 |accessdate=5 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Penang Botanic Gardens==\nIn mid-1884, following a recommendation from [[Kew Gardens]],<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> Curtis was appointed to the position as Assistant Superintendent of Forests and Gardens  under the [[Straits Settlements]] administration.<ref name=\"Jones14\">{{cite web|url = http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title = Colonial Botanic Gardens and World Heritage: the significance of the Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author = David Jones (p.14)|publisher = www.penangstory.net.my|date = April 2002|accessdate = 5 November 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date = 2011-07-22|url-status = dead}}</ref> Curtis reported to a Superintendent, [[Nathaniel Cantley]], who was also the Curator of the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]].<ref name=\"Friends\">{{cite web|url=http://www.surforever.com/botanika/index.php?page=history|title=Views from the past...|publisher=Friends of the Penang Botanic Gardens Society|accessdate=4 November 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080722025839/http://www.surforever.com/botanika/index.php?page=history|archive-date=2008-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> Curtis was placed in charge of the Penang region of the Forest and Gardens Department, which included the \"Waterfall Gardens\", together with some 3,575 ha of forest reserves. The forest reserves included areas reserved for recreational, fuel, forestry harvesting and protection purposes, mostly on [[Penang Island]]. The Forests and Gardens Department was initially engaged mainly in the cultivation of essential commercial plants, inspecting crops and advising the planting community.<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>\n\nWhen the department's work in connection with economic crops and forestry was taken over by the Agriculture and Forestry Departments, Curtis was appointed the first superintendent of the newly re-created [[Penang Botanic Gardens]],<ref>Simon Gardner, Pindar Sidisunthorn and Lai Ee May, 2011. ''Heritage Trees of Penang''. Penang: Areca Books. {{ISBN|978-967-57190-6-6}}</ref> responsible for the layout of the gardens, and their transformation from an old granite quarry site.<ref name = \"Friends\"/> The Gardens, as distinct from the Forest Reserves, became Curtis' passion. Curtis was presented with a tropical valley, including a nutmeg plantation with associated structures, and a prominent location on the trail to and at the foot of the \"Great Waterfall\". While an avid and acknowledged botanist and plant collector, he proved himself to be a creative landscape designer in crafting the design and development of the Gardens.<ref name=\"Jones15\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.15)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn accepting the position, Curtis proposed a long term strategy as to the development of the gardens and its potential role as a botanical repository and clearing house.<ref name=\"Jones17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.17)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> Curtis' immediate actions were to develop a plant nursery and undertake a programme of works to create a pleasurable recreational and botanical garden in the valley. This vision was spelt out in detail in his 1885 annual report to Cantley as part of the Department's Annual Report. This included proposals to extend and develop the existing \"Waterfall Gardens\", the construction of road circuits, the erection of plant-houses for the propagation and cultivation of various species, and the provision of recreational venues.<ref name = \"Jones17\"/>\n\nHis immediate steps in 1885&ndash;86 were focussed upon increasing the area of the Gardens in the valley together with improving road and pedestrian access. In his 1885 report, Curtis commented on ''\"the poor gravelly soil in the valley\"''<ref name = \"Jones17\"/> which required that considerable attention should be given to the preparation of the ground for tree planting. However, the ''\"natural advantages of the surroundings, from a landscape gardening point of view, ... in a great measure compensate for this defect.\"''<ref name = \"Jones17\"/>\n\nFrom the outset, Curtis introduced aesthetic considerations into the design of the Gardens, through the strategic placement of trees and the clearance of jungle. The circular road circuits he had constructed carefully weave through the valley opening up views, framing vantage points, and providing surprises to the visitor.<ref name = \"Jones17\"/> Curtis' design was motivated by his objective to take advantage of and exploit the natural landscape in the first instance, and then locate plantings in functional or species family associations.<ref name = \"Jones18\"/> A later curator, [[Frederick Sydney Banfield]], observed of  the planting design structure established by Curtis that: ''\"There is little systematic arrangement even in the botanical sections, the principal aim having been to arrange the plants in such a way as to enhance the natural beauty of the Gardens\"''.<ref name=\"Jones18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.18)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn short leaves of absence he made collections of both living and herbarium specimens at Penang, Burma and neighbouring coastal areas. On some of the trips he was accompanied by [[Henry Nicholas Ridley]], superintendent of The [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]].  Both men were interested in the development of the rubber industry, and experiments they made in Penang proved exceedingly valuable to planters.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\nCurtis' health began to deteriorate from 1890 onwards.  He took leave of absence from Penang ''\"on account of ill-health\"''<ref name = \"Jones18\"/> from 26 January to 25 December 1891. Curtis blamed his ill-health on the quality and location of the accommodation made available to him. Returning in December 1891, Curtis spent another five months at the quarters ''\"during which the health of myself and family suffered severely from fever\"''<ref name = \"Jones18\"/> forcing him to vacate the house and rent accommodation elsewhere.\n\nHis 1892 ''Annual Report'' includes ''\"A list of the more important Plants and Trees flowered in the Botanic Gardens, Penang, 1892\"'', and provides an extensive review of the flowering species in the Gardens' collection.<ref name = \"Jones14\"/> Two years later he published ''\"An Extensive Catalogue of Flowering Plants and Ferns Found Growing Wild in the island of Penang\"'' in the ''[[Journal of the Malaysian Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society|Journal of the Straits Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society]]'': containing 1,971 species of 793 genera and 129 natural orders, it is a significant record of Malaysian flora.<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>\n\nCurtis also maintained his professional association with the Veitch family during his tenure as Assistant Superintendent. Often forwarding specimens to their nursery, he always visited them while on leave in England, and [[James Herbert Veitch]] reported on the Gardens during a visit in 1896, as part of an extensive tour of inspection of South East Asian and Australasian botanic gardens and public gardens, in his ''\"Traveller's Notes\"'' (1896).<ref name = \"Jones15\"/>\n\nIn March 1903, Curtis took early long service leave due to a ''\"complete breakdown in February\"'' from fever. [[Walter Fox]] was appointed Superintendent on 7 December 1903, ''\"the date of Mr Curtis's retirement\"''.<ref name = \"Jones18\"/>\n\nFollowing his appointment, Fox reflected that Curtis' administration was one of important developments in Penang:<blockquote>\"In Curtis's retirement the Government loses an able conscientious and hardworking officer. It falls to the lot of few men on their retirement to leave their life's work in so visible and concrete a form. Eighteen years ago the site of the present beautiful Gardens was practically a waste ground. It is now the pride of the Colony and the admiration of all who visit it\".<ref name=\"Jones16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.16)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote> [[Henry Nicholas Ridley|Ridley]] recorded in 1910 that ''\"Mr Curtis was a man full of energy and skill as a landscape gardener and was not to be daunted by difficulties\"''.<ref name = \"Jones16\"/>\n\n==Retirement==\nFollowing his retirement, his main herbarium was transferred to the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]].<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> Curtis returned to England, settling in his native town of [[Barnstaple]], in Devon, where he spent his retirement tending his own collection of [[peach]] trees, [[carnation]]s, [[orchid]]s, [[sweet pea]]s, [[streptocarpus]], and [[meconopsis]] in a garden close to [[Barnstaple Victoria Road railway station]].<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 1928 he fell ill and in need of an operation in hospital. For a while it appeared as though he might make a full recovery, but five weeks after surgery, on 23 August, he died at his home at Barnstaple.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.orchids.co.in/orchidologists/charles-curtis.shtm Article on www.orchids.co.in]\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curtis, Charles}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Barnstaple]]\n[[Category:English botanists]]\n[[Category:Veitch Nurseries]]\n[[Category:Plant collectors]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles Curtis''' (1853 \u2013 23 August 1928) was an English [[botanist]] who was sent by [[James Veitch & Sons]] to search for new plant species in [[Madagascar]], [[Borneo]], [[Sumatra]], [[Java]] and the [[Moluccas]], before settling in [[Penang]], where he became the first superintendent of the [[Penang Botanic Gardens]].\n\n==Early days==\nCurtis was born in [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]],<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>  the youngest of four brothers.<ref name = \"Orchids\">{{cite web| url= http://www.orchids.co.in/orchidologists/charles-curtis.shtm|title = Charles Curtis (1853\u20131928) |author= |publisher = www.orchids.co.in|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref> His paternal grandfather, a [[Normans|Norman]] by the name of Courtois, had settled at Barnstaple many years previously. Like his brothers, Curtis worked as a garden boy at the local Bale's Nursery.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> On completing his education, Curtis joined [[James Veitch & Sons]]' Royal Exotic Nursery at [[Chelsea, London]] in 1874, where he received his botanical training in the \"New Plant Department\".<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>\n\n==Plant hunting==\nIn 1878, [[Harry Veitch]] despatched him to [[Mauritius]] and [[Madagascar]], from where he sent seeds of ''[[Nepenthes madagascariensis]]'', a species of [[pitcher plant]],<ref name = \"HV85\">{{cite book | author=[[James Herbert Veitch]]| title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher=[[Caradoc Doy]] | year=2006|edition=reprint|page=85| isbn=0-9553515-0-2}}</ref> and various other tropical plants, including ''[[Angraecum sesquipedale]]''.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> Unfortunately, following \"treachery\" by one of the African helpers, who cut the rope which held the raft on which the plants were being floated downriver, the first consignment of plants collected was lost and, as a result, the collecting work had to be repeated.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\n[[Image:MN561 A New Pitcher Plant from the Limestone Mountains of Sarawak, Borneo.jpg|thumb|left|[[Marianne North]]'s painting of ''[[Nepenthes northiana]]'', showing a lower and an upper pitcher]]\nCurtis returned to England in 1879, but a year later was sent to the [[Dutch East Indies]], where he explored [[Borneo]], [[Sumatra]], [[Java]] and the [[Moluccas]]. Veitch instructed him to collect specimens of ''[[Nepenthes northiana]]'', which had been discovered by [[Marianne North]] in Borneo, although the precise locality where the plant grew was unknown.<ref name = \"HV85\"/> On the trip to Borneo, Curtis was accompanied by a young gardener, [[David Burke (botanist)|David Burke]],<ref name = \"HV85\"/> who later became a [[plant collector]] himself. The search for the elusive pitcher plant was unsuccessful, but the pair discovered many other species, including many interesting stove ([[Greenhouse|hot-house]]) plants, palms, and orchids. At the end of the trip, Curtis accompanied Burke to [[Singapore]], from where Burke returned to England with the collection of plants, including large consignments of the  [[slipper orchid]]s, ''[[Paphiopedilum stonei]]'' and ''[[Paphiopedilum lowii|P. lowii]]'',<ref name = \"HV86\"/> as well as many [[Vanda]]s, [[Rhododendron]]s, and the beautiful foliage plant for British hot-houses, ''[[Leea amabilis]]''.<ref name = \"HV86\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=86| isbn= }}</ref><ref name = \"HV271\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=271| isbn= }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Paphiopedilum superbiens Orchi 05.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Paphiopedilum superbiens]]'' ]]\nFrom Singapore, Curtis travelled to [[Pontianak, Indonesia|Pontianak]] in Dutch Borneo, with the special object of obtaining a consignment of ''[[Phalaenopsis violacea]]'', then known in England but still rare. He was successful in locating the plant, but again, owing to a mishap with the boat, a month's collections and all his clothes and instruments were lost, and he narrowly escaped with his life.<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n\nIn 1882, Curtis eventually located ''[[Nepenthes northiana]]'' in Borneo and sent seeds back to Chelsea, as well as ''[[Nepenthes stenophylla|N. stenophylla]]'' and seed from a plant that became known as ''[[Nepenthes maxima|N. curtisii]]'', although now known as ''[[Nepenthes maxima|N. maxima]]''. Curtis was not meticulous in recording where he located individual plants \u2013 although it was originally believed that he collected ''N. curtisii'' in Borneo, [[Charles Clarke (botanist)|Charles Clarke]] points out that he also visited [[Sulawesi]] on the same trip, and ''N. maxima'' is common there.<ref name=Clarke>Clarke, C.M. 1997. ''Nepenthes of Borneo''.  Natural History Publications (Borneo), Kota Kinabalu.</ref> He also sent back the orchid which was originally named ''[[Paphiopedilum curtisii]]'',<ref name = \"OSCOV\"/> although now known as a synonym for ''[[Paphiopedilum superbiens]]'';<ref name = \"Commons\"/> Curtis did not reveal where he found the plants, other than saying that this was in [[Sumatra]].<ref name = \"OSCOV\"/>\n\nAccording to the account in ''[[Hortus Veitchii]]'', Curtis had been commissioned to go in search of ''Nepenthes northiana'', and <blockquote>\"after long and unsuccessful effort, Curtis gave up hope, under the impression that Miss North had been wrongly informed, but fortunately before leaving the district it occurred to him to look over a steep escarpment in the hill-side, accomplished by lying prostrate on the ground, when to his great joy he discovered the long-looked-for plant some distance below. He succeeded in gathering ripe capsules, and lost no time in transmitting them to Chelsea, where the seed soon germinated\",<ref name = \"HV485\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=485| isbn= }}</ref></blockquote> and was introduced in the James Veitch & Sons catalogue in 1883.\n\nOther plants introduced to England by Curtis, include two species of [[Rhododendron subgenus Vireya|Vireya rhododendron]] \u2013  ''[[Rhododendron multicolor]]'' (with the red variety ''Curtisii'' named after him)<ref name = \"HV286\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=286| isbn= }}</ref> and ''[[Rhododendron teysmannii|R. teysmannii]]'' (now considered to be subspecies of ''[[Rhododendron javanicum|R. javanicum]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.vireya.net/history.htm|title = The History of Vireya Rhododendron Culture|author= Chris Callard|publisher = www.vireya.net|date=30 April 2008|accessdate=16 December 2008}}</ref> \u2013 before he terminated his engagement with Veitch early in 1884.<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n[[Image:Nepenthes maxima Sulawesi1.jpg|200px|right|thumb|''[[Nepenthes maxima]]'']]\nAmongst the many plant species named after Curtis in recognition of his services to botany and horticulture were the following:\n \n*''[[Acanthephippium curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV111\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=111| isbn= }}</ref> \n*''[[Cirrhopetalum curtisii]]''<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.yonggee.name/Notes/Cirr_curtisii.htm|title = Cirrhopetalum curtisii|author= Orchid Species Society|publisher =www.yonggee.name|date=June 2003|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n*''[[Gastrochilus curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n*''[[Luisia curtisii]]''<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.orchidfoto.com/thumbnails.php?album=182 |title = Luisia curtisii|author= National Parks, Singapore|publisher =www.orchidfoto.com|date= |accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n*''[[Medinilla curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV273\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=273| isbn= }}</ref> \n*''[[Nepenthes curtisii]]''<ref name = \"HV86\"/> (subsequently synonymised with ''[[Nepenthes maxima]]'')\n*''[[Paphiopedilum curtisii]]''<ref name=\"OSCOV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscov.asn.au/articles2/paph3.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050508012449/http://www.oscov.asn.au/articles2/paph3.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 May 2005|title=The Lost Slippers|author=Alan Hope and Brian Milligan|publisher=Orchids Society Council of Victoria|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref><ref name = \"HV123\">{{cite book | author= | title=[[Hortus Veitchii]]| publisher= | year= |page=123| isbn= }}</ref> (subsequently synonymised with ''[[Paphiopedilum superbiens]]'')<ref name = \"Commons\">{{cite web| url= http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Paphiopedilum_superbiens|title = Paphiopedilum superbiens|author= |publisher =commons.wikimedia.org|date= |accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n*''[[Pentace curtisii]]''<ref>{{cite web| url= http://floraweb.nparks.gov.sg/search/viewDetail.action;jsessionid=1F8640C2515B9F16B08C5470E8E61742?pgId=1913590059831626&key=3| title= Pentace curtisii| author= National Parks, Singapore| publisher= www.nparks.gov.sg| date= | accessdate= 6 November 2008}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*''[[Rhododendron multicolor]]'' var. ''curtisii''<ref name = \"HV86\"/>\n*''[[Shorea curtisii]]'' (Dark Red Meranti)<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.nparks.gov.sg/cms/index.php?option=com_g2bridge&view=gallery&Itemid=94&g2_itemId=1924|title = Shorea curtisii|author= National Parks, Singapore|publisher =www.nparks.gov.sg|date= 14 May 2008|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe was also honoured by the genus ''Curtisina'',<ref name = \"Jones14\"/> but the only member of the genus, ''Curtisina penangensis'', was subsequently identified as a [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] synonym of ''[[Dacryodes longifolia]]''.<ref name = \"TKB\">{{cite web| url= https://doi.org/10.1663%2F0007-196X%282003%2954%5B266%3ANODVIA%5D2.0.CO%3B2|title = Notes on Dacryodes |author= Douglas C. Daly|publisher = SpringerLink|date= 12 February 2008 |accessdate=5 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Penang Botanic Gardens==\nIn mid-1884, following a recommendation from [[Kew Gardens]],<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> Curtis was appointed to the position as Assistant Superintendent of Forests and Gardens  under the [[Straits Settlements]] administration.<ref name=\"Jones14\">{{cite web|url = http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title = Colonial Botanic Gardens and World Heritage: the significance of the Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author = David Jones (p.14)|publisher = www.penangstory.net.my|date = April 2002|accessdate = 5 November 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date = 2011-07-22|url-status = dead}}</ref> Curtis reported to a Superintendent, [[Nathaniel Cantley]], who was also the Curator of the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]].<ref name=\"Friends\">{{cite web|url=http://www.surforever.com/botanika/index.php?page=history|title=Views from the past...|publisher=Friends of the Penang Botanic Gardens Society|accessdate=4 November 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080722025839/http://www.surforever.com/botanika/index.php?page=history|archive-date=2008-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> Curtis was placed in charge of the Penang region of the Forest and Gardens Department, which included the \"Waterfall Gardens\", together with some 3,575 ha of forest reserves. The forest reserves included areas reserved for recreational, fuel, forestry harvesting and protection purposes, mostly on [[Penang Island]]. The Forests and Gardens Department was initially engaged mainly in the cultivation of essential commercial plants, inspecting crops and advising the planting community.<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>\n\nWhen the department's work in connection with economic crops and forestry was taken over by the Agriculture and Forestry Departments, Curtis was appointed the first superintendent of the newly re-created [[Penang Botanic Gardens]],<ref>Simon Gardner, Pindar Sidisunthorn and Lai Ee May, 2011. ''Heritage Trees of Penang''. Penang: Areca Books. {{ISBN|978-967-57190-6-6}}</ref> responsible for the layout of the gardens, and their transformation from an old granite quarry site.<ref name = \"Friends\"/> The Gardens, as distinct from the Forest Reserves, became Curtis' passion. Curtis was presented with a tropical valley, including a nutmeg plantation with associated structures, and a prominent location on the trail to and at the foot of the \"Great Waterfall\". While an avid and acknowledged botanist and plant collector, he proved himself to be a creative landscape designer in crafting the design and development of the Gardens.<ref name=\"Jones15\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.15)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn accepting the position, Curtis proposed a long term strategy as to the development of the gardens and its potential role as a botanical repository and clearing house.<ref name=\"Jones17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.17)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> Curtis' immediate actions were to develop a plant nursery and undertake a programme of works to create a pleasurable recreational and botanical garden in the valley. This vision was spelt out in detail in his 1885 annual report to Cantley as part of the Department's Annual Report. This included proposals to extend and develop the existing \"Waterfall Gardens\", the construction of road circuits, the erection of plant-houses for the propagation and cultivation of various species, and the provision of recreational venues.<ref name = \"Jones17\"/>\n\nHis immediate steps in 1885&ndash;86 were focussed upon increasing the area of the Gardens in the valley together with improving road and pedestrian access. In his 1885 report, Curtis commented on ''\"the poor gravelly soil in the valley\"''<ref name = \"Jones17\"/> which required that considerable attention should be given to the preparation of the ground for tree planting. However, the ''\"natural advantages of the surroundings, from a landscape gardening point of view, ... in a great measure compensate for this defect.\"''<ref name = \"Jones17\"/>\n\nFrom the outset, Curtis introduced aesthetic considerations into the design of the Gardens, through the strategic placement of trees and the clearance of jungle. The circular road circuits he had constructed carefully weave through the valley opening up views, framing vantage points, and providing surprises to the visitor.<ref name = \"Jones17\"/> Curtis' design was motivated by his objective to take advantage of and exploit the natural landscape in the first instance, and then locate plantings in functional or species family associations.<ref name = \"Jones18\"/> A later curator, [[Frederick Sydney Banfield]], observed of  the planting design structure established by Curtis that: ''\"There is little systematic arrangement even in the botanical sections, the principal aim having been to arrange the plants in such a way as to enhance the natural beauty of the Gardens\"''.<ref name=\"Jones18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.18)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn short leaves of absence he made collections of both living and herbarium specimens at Penang, Burma and neighbouring coastal areas. On some of the trips he was accompanied by [[Henry Nicholas Ridley]], superintendent of The [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]].  Both men were interested in the development of the rubber industry, and experiments they made in Penang proved exceedingly valuable to planters.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\nCurtis' health began to deteriorate from 1890 onwards.  He took leave of absence from Penang ''\"on account of ill-health\"''<ref name = \"Jones18\"/> from 26 January to 25 December 1891. Curtis blamed his ill-health on the quality and location of the accommodation made available to him. Returning in December 1891, Curtis spent another five months at the quarters ''\"during which the health of myself and family suffered severely from fever\"''<ref name = \"Jones18\"/> forcing him to vacate the house and rent accommodation elsewhere.\n\nHis 1892 ''Annual Report'' includes ''\"A list of the more important Plants and Trees flowered in the Botanic Gardens, Penang, 1892\"'', and provides an extensive review of the flowering species in the Gardens' collection.<ref name = \"Jones14\"/> Two years later he published ''\"An Extensive Catalogue of Flowering Plants and Ferns Found Growing Wild in the island of Penang\"'' in the ''[[Journal of the Malaysian Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society|Journal of the Straits Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society]]'': containing 1,971 species of 793 genera and 129 natural orders, it is a significant record of Malaysian flora.<ref name = \"Jones14\"/>\n\nCurtis also maintained his professional association with the Veitch family during his tenure as Assistant Superintendent. Often forwarding specimens to their nursery, he always visited them while on leave in England, and [[James Herbert Veitch]] reported on the Gardens during a visit in 1896, as part of an extensive tour of inspection of South East Asian and Australasian botanic gardens and public gardens, in his ''\"Traveller's Notes\"'' (1896).<ref name = \"Jones15\"/>\n\nIn March 1903, Curtis took early long service leave due to a ''\"complete breakdown in February\"'' from fever. [[Walter Fox]] was appointed Superintendent on 7 December 1903, ''\"the date of Mr Curtis's retirement\"''.<ref name = \"Jones18\"/>\n\nFollowing his appointment, Fox reflected that Curtis' administration was one of important developments in Penang:<blockquote>\"In Curtis's retirement the Government loses an able conscientious and hardworking officer. It falls to the lot of few men on their retirement to leave their life's work in so visible and concrete a form. Eighteen years ago the site of the present beautiful Gardens was practically a waste ground. It is now the pride of the Colony and the admiration of all who visit it\".<ref name=\"Jones16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|title=The Penang 'Waterfall' Botanic Gardens|author=David Jones (p.16)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722233625/http://www.penangstory.net.my/docs/Abs-DavidJones.doc|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote> [[Henry Nicholas Ridley|Ridley]] recorded in 1910 that ''\"Mr Curtis was a man full of energy and skill as a landscape gardener and was not to be daunted by difficulties\"''.<ref name = \"Jones16\"/>\n\n==Retirement==\nFollowing his retirement, his main herbarium was transferred to the [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]].<ref name = \"Orchids\"/> Curtis returned to England, settling in his native town of [[Barnstaple]], in Devon, where he spent his retirement tending his own collection of [[peach]] trees, [[carnation]]s, [[orchid]]s, [[sweet pea]]s, [[streptocarpus]], and [[meconopsis]] in a garden close to [[Barnstaple Victoria Road railway station]].<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 1928 he fell ill and in need of an operation in hospital. For a while it appeared as though he might make a full recovery, but five weeks after surgery, on 23 August, he died at his home at Barnstaple.<ref name = \"Orchids\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.orchids.co.in/orchidologists/charles-curtis.shtm Article on www.orchids.co.in]\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curtis, Charles}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Barnstaple]]\n[[Category:English botanists]]\n[[Category:Veitch Nurseries]]\n[[Category:Plant collectors]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Curtis_(botanist)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Indonesia}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Indonesia.svg|500px\n| legend1         = Map of provinces with coronavirus cases (as of 3 April){{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}} {{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Indonesia (Density).svg\n| legend2         = Map of provinces with confirmed coronavirus cases (as of 3 April)\n{{legend|#C8C8C8|No confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#FCEED3|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#E5354B|100-999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|darkred|1,000+ confirmed cases}}\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Indonesia]]\n| first_case      = [[Kemang, Jakarta]]\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| arrival_date    = 2 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=02|year1=2020|month2=04|day2=04|year=2020}})\n| recovery_cases  = 134<ref name=\"InaCOVID-19\">[http://covid19.bnpb.go.id Dashboard Pemantauan Kasus COVID-19]</ref>\n| deaths          = 181<ref name=\"InaCOVID-19\"/>\n| active_cases    = 1,671<ref name=\"InaCOVID-19\"/>\n| territories     = 32 provinces, see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia#Cases by province|below]]\n| confirmed_cases = 1,986<ref name=\"InaCOVID-19\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = <!-- List only national websites here! For local websites, see Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Indonesia medical cases#Cases by province -->\nNational:<br />{{URL|covid19.go.id}}<br />{{URL|covid19.bnpb.go.id}}<br />{{URL|covid19.kemkes.go.id}}<br />Local:<br />[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia#Cases by province|see cases by province]]<br /><br />'''[[WhatsApp]] bot'''<br />+6281133399000<br /><br />'''[[Hotline]] '''<br />119 EXT 9<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://tirto.id/update-corona-9-maret-hotline-baru-covid-19-di-indonesia-119-ext-9-eDP7\n|title=Update Corona 9 Maret: Hotline Baru COVID-19 di Indonesia 119 EXT 9\n|author=Dipna Videlia Putsanra\n|work=Tirto.id\n|date=9 March 2020\n|accessdate=2 April 2020\n}}</ref><br /><br />'''Volunteer Registration '''<br />http://deskrelawanpb.bnpb.go.id/covid-19/<br /><br />\n| First Case detected: = 2 March 2020\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Indonesia]] on 2 March 2020.<ref name=\"theguardian-ratcliffe\">{{cite web|accessdate=2020-03-02|title=First coronavirus cases confirmed in Indonesia amid fears nation is ill-prepared for an outbreak|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/02/first-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-indonesia-amid-fears-nation-is-ill-prepared-for-outbreak|date=2 March 2020|website=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Bangkok Post Public Company|last1=Limited|accessdate=2020-03-02|title=Indonesia confirms first cases of coronavirus|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/world/1869789/indonesia-confirms-first-cases-of-coronavirus|website=www.bangkokpost.com}}</ref> As of 3 April, the pandemic has spread to all provinces in Indonesia, except [[East Nusa Tenggara]] and [[Gorontalo]]. All had reported suspected cases.\n\nSo far, Indonesia has recorded 181 deaths, more than any other [[Southeast Asia]]n country. Its fatality rate is also one of the highest in the world. Researchers suggest the main reason for the high rate is probably a lack of testing, resulting in many cases going undetected.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-23/why-is-indonesia-coronavirus-death-rate-highest-in-world/12079040\n|title=Why is Indonesia Coronavirus Death Rate the Highest in the World\n|author=Anne Barker and Hellena Souisa\n|work=ABC News\n|date=23 March 2020\n|accessdate=1 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Indonesia medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\nThe positive cases first confirmed in March are not the first Indonesians to have been infected with the SARS-CoV-2 virus. In January, an Indonesian [[domestic helper|maid]] in [[Singapore]] contracted the virus from her employer.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/seasia/2020/02/04/indonesian-maid-in-singapore-tests-positive-for-coronavirus.html\n|title=Indonesian maid in Singapore tests positive for coronavirus\n|author=Agence France-Presse\n|work=The Jakarta Post\n|date=2020-02-04\n|accessdate=2020-03-05\n}}</ref>\n\nA man from the [[Netherlands]] may have been the first confirmed coronavirus patient in Indonesia when he fell ill there in January. He was treated in three hospitals while he was ill in East Java in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/1325449/dutch-man-possibly-early-corona-patient-in-indonesia|title=Dutch Man Possibly Early Corona Patient in Indonesia|last=Bhwana|first=Petir Garda|date=2020-03-30|website=Tempo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/indonesia/indonesia-52063862|title=Cek fakta: Benarkah ada warga Belanda positif corona yang tak teridentifikasi di Jawa Timur?|date=2020-03-27|work=BBC News Indonesia|access-date=2020-03-31|language=id}}</ref> \n\nAn 11-year-old girl who died at the Slamet Martodirdjo Hospital in Pamekasan in Madura Island in East Java on March 20 has been confirmed as the youngest COVID-19 fatality in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/31/east-java-girl-11-becomes-youngest-covid-19-fatality-in-indonesia.html|title=East Java girl, 11, becomes youngest COVID-19 fatality in Indonesia|last=Post|first=The Jakarta|website=The Jakarta Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nThe first confirmed death of coronavirus in the country occurred on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"death2\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4934606/pasien-corona-kasus-25-meninggal-dunia-di-rsup-sanglah-bali|title=Pasien Corona Kasus 25 Meninggal Dunia di RSUP Sanglah Bali|author=Angga Riza|date=2020-03-11|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> However, one of [[Telkom Indonesia|Telkom]] employees died on 3 March when tested positive COVID-19 on 14 March and also infecting his wife and child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.detik.com/berita-ekonomi-bisnis/d-4940364/telkom-buka-suara-ada-karyawannya-meninggal-positif-corona|title=Telkom Buka Suara Ada Karyawannya Meninggal Positif Corona|last=Afriyadi|first=Achmad Dwi|website=detikfinance|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4940514/istri-anak-pegawai-telkom-yang-meninggal-di-cianjur-juga-kena-corona|title=Istri-Anak Pegawai Telkom yang Meninggal di Cianjur Juga Kena Corona|last=Mawardi|first=Isal|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n\n====2 February====\n* The Indonesian government evacuated 243 Indonesian nationals from [[Wuhan]], [[China]]. The repatriated Indonesians were placed under quarantine in the [[Natuna Regency|Natuna Islands]] but were not tested as they were asymptomatic.<ref name=\"Feb2020\">{{cite web \n|title=Indonesian Government Successfully Repatriated 243 People From Wuhan China {{!}} Portal Kementerian Luar Negeri Republik Indonesia \n|url=https://kemlu.go.id/portal/en/read/1011/berita/indonesian-government-successfully-repatriated-243-people-from-wuhan-china \n|website=kemlu.go.id \n|publisher=MINISTRY OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS OF THE REPUBLIC OF INDONESIA \n|accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/indonesia-finally-reports-two-coronavirus-cases-scientists-worry-it-has-many-more|first=Dyna|last= Rochmyaningsih|date=3 March 2020|title=Indonesia finally reports two coronavirus cases. Scientists worry it has many more|work=American Association for the Advancement of Science|accessdate=3 March 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n====24 February====\n* 9 Indonesians on board the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' tested positive for the virus and were moved to treatment facilities in [[Japan]]. The Indonesian government repatriated and then quarantined the remaining 68 crew members, along with the 188 from the ''[[World Dream]]'', onto the uninhabited Sebaru Kecil Island in the [[Thousand Islands (Indonesia)|Thousand Islands]] off the coast of [[Jakarta]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/02/24/number-of-indonesians-with-coronavirus-on-diamond-princess-rises-to-nine.html\n|title=Number of Indonesians with coronavirus on Diamond Princess rises to nine\n|author1=Marchio Irfan Gorbiano\n|author2=Budi Sutrisno \n|work=The Jakarta Post\n|date=2020-02-24\n|accessdate=2020-03-05\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.cnbcindonesia.com/news/20200224144659-4-140074/wni-kena-corona-di-kapal-diamond-princess-kini-jadi-9-orang \n|title=WNI Kena Corona di Kapal Diamond Princess Kini Jadi 9 orang\n|trans-title=Indonesian Citizens Affected by Corona on the Diamond Princess Ship are now 9 people\n|work=CNBC Indonesia\n|date=24 February 2020\n|accessdate=24 February 2020\n|language=id\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n[[File:CoViD-19 ID.svg|thumb|upright=2|left|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]].]]\n\n====2 March====\n* President [[Joko Widodo]] confirmed the first two cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in the country in a televised statement.<ref name=\"straitstimes\">{{cite news |author=Linda Yulisman |title=Mother and daughter test positive for coronavirus in Indonesia, first confirmed cases in the country |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/indonesia-confirms-two-coronavirus-cases-president |accessdate=2 March 2020 |work=The Straits Times |issue=Asia |date=2 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> According to the Minister of Health [[Terawan Agus Putranto]], the patients contracted the virus from an infected Japanese person in [[Depok]] who later tested positive in [[Malaysia]].<ref name=\"theguardian-ratcliffe\" /> Both Indonesian patients were subsequently hospitalized at Sulianti Saroso Infection Center Hospital, [[North Jakarta]].\n\n====6 March====\n* As of 6 March, Indonesia had only tested 450 individuals out of its 270 million population.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://infeksiemerging.kemkes.go.id/uncategorized/situasi-terkini-perkembangan-coronavirus-disease-covid-19-6-maret-2020\n|title=Situasi Terkini Perkembangan Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) 6 Maret 2020\n|work=Info Infeksi Emerging Kementerian Kesehatan RI\n|language=id\n|date=2020-03-06\n|accessdate=2020-03-06\n}}</ref>\n\n====7 March====\n* One of the crew evacuated from the ''Diamond Princess'' was suspected of contracting the disease and was subsequently transferred to an isolation unit at Persahabatan Central General Hospital, [[East Jakarta]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jakartaglobe.id/news/another-diamond-princess-crew-member-from-indonesia-suspected-of-contracting-coronavirus|title=Another Diamond Princess Crew Member From Indonesia Suspected of Contracting Coronavirus|website=Jakarta Globe|date=2020-03-06|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n====8 March====\n* A 50-year-old woman from Jakarta tested positive in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. She began showing symptoms two days after flying to [[Perth]] from Jakarta on 27 February and saw a GP four days after arriving in Melbourne on 2 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/indonesian-woman-becomes-12th-victorian-covid-19-case-20200308-p54809.html|title=Indonesian woman becomes 12th Victorian COVID-19 case|work=The Age|language=en|date=2020-03-08|accessdate=2020-03-08|first=Tate|last=Papworth}}</ref>\n* The government of Indonesia announced two more confirmed cases. One patient was infected through close contact with case #1, the other patient being a crew member of the Diamond Princess.<ref name=\"8Mar20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200308162030-20-481536/pasien-positif-virus-corona-bertambah-jadi-6-orang|title=Pasien Positif Corona Bertambah Jadi 6 Orang|work=CNN Indonesia|language=id|date=2020-03-08|accessdate=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n====9 March====\n* Indonesia confirmed 13 new cases of COVID-19 infection, 2 of them being foreigners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4931659/melonjak-pasien-positif-corona-di-wilayah-ri-jadi-19-orang|title=Melonjak! Pasien Positif Corona di Wilayah RI Jadi 19 Orang|author=Andhika Prasetia |website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-09|date=2020-03-09}}</ref> The Indonesian government decided not to disclose the detection location of the patient and the treatment facility used.{{citation  needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n====10 March====\n* 2 patients who were previously confirmed to be positive were subsequently reported as negative, substantiating an explanation made by an Indonesian government representative. The two patients were to be discharged, should further test confirm their negative status.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/internasional/d-4932718/kabar-baik-pasien-kasus-06-dan-14-sudah-negatif-corona|title=Kabar Baik! Pasien Kasus 06 dan 14 Sudah Negatif Corona|author=Kadek Melda Luxiana|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-10|date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n*Indonesia confirmed 8 new cases of COVID-19 infection, 2 of them foreigners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4933267/jadi-27-orang-ini-detail-8-pasien-baru-virus-corona|title=Jadi 27 Orang, Ini Detail 8 Pasien Baru Virus Corona|author=Kadek Melda Luxiana|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-10|date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n*A suspected COVID-19 patient fleed from Persahabatan Central General Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4937896/pasien-positif-corona-kabur-dari-rs-persahabatan-dijemput-keluarga|title=Pasien Positif Corona Kabur dari RS Persahabatan, Dijemput Keluarga|last=Luqman|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4937970/alasan-pasien-positif-corona-kabur-tak-mau-sekamar-isolasi-berdua|title=Alasan Pasien Positif Corona Kabur: Tak Mau Sekamar Isolasi Berdua|last=Arunata|first=Luqman Nurhadi|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> She was later confirmed as positive of the virus and has returned to the hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4938404/pasien-corona-yang-sempat-kabur-dipastikan-sudah-kembali-ke-rs-persahabatan|title=Pasien Corona yang Sempat Kabur Dipastikan Sudah Kembali ke RS Persahabatan|last=Luxiana|first=Kadek Melda|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n====11 March====\n* Case #25 died due to complications of the disease.<ref name=death>{{Cite web|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/11/13061741/breaking-news-satu-pasien-covid-19-di-indonesia-meninggal-dunia|title=BREAKING NEWS: Satu Pasien Covid-19 di Indonesia Meninggal Dunia|author=Ihsanuddin|website=Kompas.com|language=id|access-date=2020-03-11|date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The victim was a British national and died in [[Bali]]'s hospital.<ref name=death2/>\n*Indonesia confirmed 7 new cases of COVID-19 infection, all of them imported cases.<ref name=:34>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4934881/pasien-positif-virus-corona-jadi-34-orang-2-sembuh-1-meninggal|title=Pasien Positif Virus Corona Jadi 34 Orang: 2 Sembuh, 1 Meninggal|author=Kanavino Ahmad Rizqo |website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n====12 March====\n* 5 cases recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4936834/data-terbaru-corona-terkait-indonesia-12-maret-2020-pukul-2100-wib/3|title=Data Terbaru Corona Terkait Indonesia, 12 Maret 2020 Pukul 21.00 WIB|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n*[[:id:Daftar Menteri Ketenagakerjaan Indonesia|Indonesian Labour Minister]] [[:id:Ida Fauziyah|Ida Fauziah]] mandated that all Indonesian companies provide their employees with coronavirus prevention equipment, such as face masks and hand sanitizer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.detik.com/berita-ekonomi-bisnis/d-4935342/perusahaan-wajib-sediakan-masker-demi-cegah-corona|title=Perusahaan Wajib Sediakan Masker Demi Cegah Corona|last=Indraini|first=Anisa|website=detikfinance|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n====13 March====\n* 3 coronavirus-linked deaths were reported, 1 case in [[Surakarta|Solo]], [[Central Java]].<ref name=death3>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kompas.com/tren/read/2020/03/13/120826665/satu-pasien-isolasi-yang-meninggal-di-rsud-moewardi-solo-positif-corona|title=Satu Pasien Isolasi yang Meninggal di RSUD Moewardi Solo Positif Corona|author=Labib Zamani|website=Kompas.com|language=id|access-date=2020-03-13|date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.detik.com/berita-detikhealth/d-4937577/ini-detail-pasien-virus-corona-yang-meninggal-di-solo|title=Ini Detail Pasien Virus Corona yang Meninggal di Solo|author=Firdaus Anwar|website=Detik.com|language=id|access-date=2020-03-13|date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The other two were undisclosed.<ref name=\"Andhika Prasetia\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4938023/kasus-positif-corona-di-ri-jadi-69|title=Kasus Positif Corona di RI Jadi 69|author=Andhika Prasetia|website=Detik.com|date=2020-03-13|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4938060/total-4-pasien-positif-corona-meninggal-dunia|title=Total 4 Pasien Positif Corona Meninggal Dunia|author=Zunita Putri|website=Detik.com|date=2020-03-13|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n* Indonesia confirmed 35 new cases of COVID-19 infection, totalling 69 cases.<ref name=\"Andhika Prasetia\"/>\n* The first affected medical worker died on 13 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/14/18404141/yurianto-ada-petugas-medis-positif-corona-yang-meninggal-dunia|title=Yurianto: Ada Petugas Medis Positif Corona yang Meninggal Dunia|website=Kompas.com|language=id|access-date=2020-03-14|date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n====14 March====\n* The Indonesian government confirmed 27 new cases of COVID-19, a total of 96 cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.detik.com/berita-detikhealth/d-4939115/ada-27-kasus-baru-pasien-positif-corona-di-indonesia-jadi-96-orang|title=Ada 27 Kasus Baru, Pasien Positif Corona di Indonesia Jadi 96 Orang|last=Rahayu|first=Lisye Sri|website=detikHealth|language=id|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> \n* This date also marks the first time that the government announced the locations with confirmed coronavirus cases. Locations with confirmed coronavirus cases included every district in [[Jakarta]], [[Tangerang]] in [[Banten]], [[Bandung]] in [[West Java]], [[Surakarta|Solo]] in [[Central Java]], [[Yogyakarta]] in [[Special Region of Yogyakarta]], [[Pontianak, West Kalimantan|Pontianak]] in [[West Kalimantan]], [[Manado]] in [[North Sulawesi]] and [[Bali]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Daerah yang Terdapat Positif Corona: dari Bandung ke Manado|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200314164544-20-483432/daerah-yang-terdapat-positif-corona-dari-bandung-ke-manado|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 3 further patients recovered, for a total of 8 recovered patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/14/16452961/update-tambah-3-total-8-orang-sembuh-dari-corona-di-indonesia|title=UPDATE: Tambah 3, Total 8 Orang Sembuh dari Corona di Indonesia|author=Ihsanuddin |website=Kompas.com|language=id|access-date=2020-03-14|date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n* 1 patient died, bringing the total to 5 deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4939143/pasien-meninggal-akibat-corona-di-ri-bertambah-jadi-5|title=Pasien Meninggal Akibat Corona di RI Bertambah Jadi 5|author=Rahel Narda Chatrine|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-14|date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n* [[Ministry of Transportation (Indonesia)|Indonesian Minister of Transportation]], [[Budi Karya Sumadi]] tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4939392/menhub-budi-karya-pasien-positif-corona-kasus-76|title=Menhub Budi Karya Pasien Positif Corona Kasus 76|author=Andhika Prasetia|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Menhub Budi Karya Sumadi positif COVID-19 |url=https://www.antaranews.com/berita/1356658/menhub-budi-karya-sumadi-positif-covid-19|language=id |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Antara News |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> A few days prior, on 10 March, Budi Karya was diagnosed with typhoid fever after travelling to [[Wakatobi Regency|Wakatobi]], [[Toraja]], [[Luwuk]], [[Makassar]], [[Parepare]], [[Kertajati International Airport|Kertajati]], and [[Indramayu]]. His travel history included travel to [[Kertajati International Airport]] on 1 March that had acted as an evacuation centre for the repatriated crew of the Diamond Princess. One of the crew of Diamond Princess tested positive for COVID-19 on 8 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4933161/menhub-jatuh-sakit-jubir-kena-gejala-tifus|title=Menhub Jatuh Sakit, Jubir: Kena Gejala Tifus|last=Prasetia|first=Andhika|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> On 11 March, Budi had also met with the Dutch Minister of Infrastructure and Water Management [[Cora van Nieuwenhuizen|Cora Van Nieuwenhuize]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4939440/menhub-sempat-ke-istana-bertemu-pejabat-belanda-sebelum-positif-corona|title=Menhub Sempat ke Istana-Bertemu Pejabat Belanda Sebelum Positif Corona|last=Prasetia|first=Andhika|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n====15 March====\n* Indonesia confirmed 21 new cases of COVID-19 infection, 19 in [[Jakarta]] and 2 in [[Central Java]], a total of 117 cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200315133445-20-483573/21-kasus-baru-pasien-positif-corona-indonesia-jadi-117-orang|title=21 Kasus Baru, Pasien Positif Corona Indonesia Jadi 117 Orang|work=CNN Indonesia|language=id|date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4939844/pasien-positif-corona-bertambah-21-kasus-total-jadi-117-kasus|title=Pasien Positif Corona Bertambah 21 Kasus, Total Jadi 117 Kasus|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-15|date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n*Indonesian President [[Joko Widodo]] is said to be undergoing a COVID-19 test in the evening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4939909/presiden-jokowi-jalani-tes-virus-corona-sore-ini|title=Presiden Jokowi Jalani Tes Virus Corona Sore Ini|website=Detik.com|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-15|date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n====16 March====\n* Indonesian Vice-President [[Ma'ruf Amin]] and Indonesian Interior Minister [[Tito Karnavian]] have tested negative on the COVID-19 test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/16/10390031/sudah-tes-wapres-maruf-amin-negatif-covid-19|title=Sudah Tes, Wapres Ma'ruf Amin Negatif Covid-19|author=Deti Mega Purnamasari|editor=Diamanty Meiliana|website=Kompas.com|language=id|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbcindonesia.com/news/20200316140224-4-145183/usai-tes-covid-19-di-rspad-tito-istri-dipastikan-sehat|title=Usai Tes Covid-19 di RSPAD, Tito & Istri Dipastikan Sehat|last=Iqbal|first=Muhammad|website=news|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n*Indonesia confirmed 17 new cases of infection,